To begin with, we define the matrix \emph{B} using the result from part
(c):

\texttt{~~~B~=~{[}-1~-1;~1~0;~0~1{]};}

Then, use the formula for the projection matrix to define \emph{P}:

\texttt{~~~P~=~B*inv(B'*B)*B';}

This solves (i). Note that all possible choices of \emph{B} would have
resulted in the same projection matrix \emph{P}. Finally, the vector
\emph{x} in \emph{S} closest to \emph{{[}0, 1, 0{]}\textsuperscript{T}}
is the projection of that vector onto \emph{S}, that is:

\texttt{~~~x~=~P*{[}0;~1;~0{]}}
